This interests me greatly and I thank you for sharing. It is obvious, as @clavemscientiae would say, that the original purpose of such gyms was not the mere obtaining of physical strength, but it was a kind of divine ritual, a means to commune with God.

The Dervish-like spinning dance obviously can be used as means to reach a state of ecstasy, but from a purely physical perspective it must be quite the oblique/core exercise. A similar machine exists in modern bodybuilding but has nowadays mostly fallen out of favor

The Indian club training is a classic method that I do not really respect, as I said in my first post its original meaning was not pure utility/efficiency so using one today would most be LARPing. The spinning still makes me wonder what effects it could have on stuff like CNS etc

Thread: On upcoming fitness/dietary trends that are going to appear in the near future. If you wish to make a living as an entrepreneur in the health industry, you can capitalize on these.

I do not mind giving this information, I am not going to be needing it for my own works.

1.5 

One of the exercises that I can see getting the most popular would be the weighted dead hang. It is easy to understand, with visible progress (heavier weights) unlike the stretches, and easy/unembarrassing for a man to do in a regular gym.

1. Spinal decompression

I have already seen this talked about in some circles. Some of the claims that are going to be made about it are it making you 1-2 inches taller, which would be enough to interest most males ages 18-25. The method consists mostly of yoga-like stretches.

3. Calves exercise

With the neck/traps training already being popularized, one of the few remaining "undiscovered" muscles will be the calves. Plenty of famous routines include a random calf exercise thrown in on leg day so people already have a basic idea about it...

2.5.

This is where mushrooms can come in. Most people know way too little about mushrooms and the different species, so with some good branding a mushroom-heavy diet might be the new "magic solution". Different mushrooms will be given different benefits, recipe books published..

2. Mushrooms

Veganism is exhausted and carnivore diets are soon going to follow suit. With both having lost their exotic appeal, people, instead of realizing that they should simply follow a classic "boring" balanced diet, will look for newer and wilder nutritional advice.

5. Honey

People are used to the store-bought brand honey and do not realize the richness and variety in the thousands kinds of honey. Its numerous health benefits are slept upon (with exception of mommy blog/more female-oriented spaces) and its rediscovery will be huge.

4. Facial exercise

With mewing/chewing exercise already being "killed" the next thing coming will be facial exercise. People love to try to focus on the few aspects they can not change and most are too scared to get actual plastic surgery so facial exercise can quickly go big.

3.5

Calf-heavy leg day routines, combining calf training with "greasing the groove" method, "the one important muscle you have never trained properly" videos can all be expected.

3.5

... but due to the hard-growing nature of the muscle almost no one "basic lifter" has seen any real progress. You can expect stuff said like: "Most people train their legs but they are not visible under your shorts anyways, focus on calves to really look good".

6. Blood occlusion training

An innovative training method which has already seen the light of day. It can give TREMENDOUS pumps, even though I am not too sure about its actual effects and safety, and will 100% be sold as a pro/expert trick.

The list is short, but I sincerely believe most of these should hit the big youtube channels/fitness blogs in the few coming years, and if you really plan on becoming a fitness personality or a brand, these, if marketed properly, will bring you a giant following. GL

6.5

This one is already hitting the lifting community and will be the easiest to capitalize upon. People love to focus on complicated stuff that has minimal effect, just to squeeze every gain possible, without realizing they would be better off simply sleeping more or eating.

Psychotherapy is an abominable perversion of the mystery of confession - but there is no redemption, no true forgiveness. At the end of the talk with the priest, your sins are forgiven by the Lord - at the end of therapy, there is nothing. The bell rings - and your session ends.

Even from a purely scientific perspective the non-secular version is the superior one. The "placebo" of having your burdens taken off is far more beneficial for your mind that simply having shared them with a stranger. There is a culmination, a barrier, a doorstep - do you see?
